RUDZANI MATSHILI
rudzani.matshili@inl.co.za FORMER  private security guards at the Steve Biko Academic Hospital, who were dismissed following allegations of misconduct in 2017, picketed outside the health facility. More than 60 dismissed officials had last month warned hospital management they intended to cause more disruptions. They danced and chanted outside the facility. No services were disrupted according to hospital management. Police were deployed to maintain order. The officials were employed by Born to Protect security company and fired after they went on strike late last year, claiming they had not been paid for three months. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  Some of them complained of not being paid at all. Hospital management terminated the services of the security company and replaced it with Vimba Security Services last year. The Academic Professional Staff Association said the guards had been without jobs since then. The organisation’s Phauwe Phosa told the Pretoria News that they had no intention of causing disruptions and that they merely wanted to know when the officials would be reinstated. Union representatives met with hospital management to discuss way forward. The hospital had obtained an emergency court interdict against group.